<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-07-13T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-07-13T23:00:00-05:00" n="618" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d618">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.6363 Manchuria/23: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-14T12:00:00+08:00">July 14,
                                1934—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received July 14—7:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>304. Department’s 112, July 5, 6 p.m. to Tokyo regarding petroleum
                            monopoly. British Legation informs me that British Consulate [at] Mukden
                            has now been instructed to make representations to Vice Minister for
                            Foreign Affairs at Hsinching leaving with him an unaddressed memorandum
                            in the sense of item (<hi rend="italic">e</hi>) of Tokyo’s 142, July 3,
                            6 p.m. to the Department.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>